After the bombings in Nairobi and Dar, the US retaliated by striking Sudan's pharmaceutical factory, sparking outrage.
Many believed Clinton's actions were to divert attention from his personal issues.
Sudan condemned the attacks, denying any involvement in terrorism.
The Sudanese government vowed to file complaints with the UN and Arab League.
Despite American claims, Sudan insisted the destroyed factory produced pharmaceuticals, not chemical weapons.
The situation escalated as Sudan called for a fact-finding mission from the US.
Amidst the chaos, tensions rose as Sudanese citizens criticized the US for interfering in their affairs.
